observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:

Re-assess established policy to ensure equitable distribution of financial assistance among the qualified beneficiaries;

Ensure that only the MSWDO personnel assess and evaluate applicants requesting financial assistance out of the AICS program including the determination of the amount of assistance to be granted;

Establish partnerships with stakeholders such as hospitals, drugstores/ pharmacies, transport companies/travel agencies, funeral parlors and other service providers to ensure that referred clients are able to receive the needed services immediately. Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) may be entered into by the LGU with qualified service providers in accordance with pertinent regulations.

We recommended and Management, through the Local Chief Executive and other concerned officials, agreed to:
Coordinate with the NHA and discuss possible actions to fast-track the implementation of the project;
Henceforth, consider the special circumstances for contract time extension provided in the Procurement Manual for LGUs, Volume III and approve the request of the contractor after due investigation and finding the request justified;
Take note of the rules on contract suspension and the grounds for suspension of work by the LGU and by the contractor provided in the Procurement Manual for LGUs, Volume III; and
Observe the provisions in Annex “E” of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 on the Contract Implementation Guidelines for the Procurement of Infrastructure Projects and other related issuances particularly Item 4.2 of GPPB Circular No. 03-2019 to ensure the timely implementation of infrastructure projects and effective management of the performance of contractors.

We recommended that management:

Require the following officials to submit the report and the record: 

The Inventory Committee on the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);

The Property Unit on the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking and Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;

The Accounting Unit on the Journal Entry Vouchers drawn for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any and other necessary adjusting entries; 

Require the General Services Unit to prepare and submit the Report on Local Road Network; and the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System at the end of the accounting period; and

3. Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of property on Land and Land Improvements.

We recommended that the management:

Require the Municipal GSO and/ or other responsible officials to obtain from the donor/s Deed/s of Donation and require the Municipal Accountant to record the items at its fair value;

Streamline and document its donation policy and process thru the issuance of an Executive Order or a Memorandum which among others, would contain the employees authorized to receive donations and their reportorial responsibilities.

We recommended that management:

Establish specific guidelines on the grants of AICS to indigent constituents which shall be in line with DSWD Memorandum Circular No. 2019-11, series of 2019: Revised Guidelines on the Implementation of Assistance to Individuals in Crisis Situation to ensure equitable distribution of financial assistance among the qualified beneficiaries;

Ensure that only the MSWDO personnel assess and evaluate applicants requesting financial assistance out of the AICS program including the determination of the amount of assistance to be granted;

Establish partnerships with stakeholders such as hospitals, drugstores/ pharmacies, transport companies/travel agencies, funeral parlors and other service providers to ensure that referred clients are able to receive the needed services immediately. Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) may be entered into by the LGU with qualified service providers in accordance with pertinent regulations.

We recommended that management:

i. Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the iTax service-provider for a system’s upgrade with the two-fold goal to hasten data processing and provide additional program functions; otherwise, consider sourcing another service provider to deliver the needed service;

ii. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accountant the List of Basic RPT Delinquencies since C.Y. 2002, as reference of the accountant’s adjustment in the RPT and SET receivables.

We recommended that management:
1. Require the following officials to submit the report and the record:
The Inventory Committee on the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
The Property Unit on the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking and Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
The Accounting Unit on the Journal Entry Vouchers drawn for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any and other necessary adjusting entries;
2. Require the General Services Unit to prepare and submit the Report on Local Road Network; and the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System at the end of the accounting period; and
3. Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of property on Land and Land Improvements.

We recommended that management:
Re-assess established policy to ensure equitable distribution of financial assistance among the qualified beneficiaries;
Ensure that only the MSWDO personnel assess and evaluate applicants requesting financial assistance out of the AICS program including the determination of the amount of assistance to be granted;
Establish partnerships with stakeholders such as hospitals, drugstores/pharmacies, transport companies/travel agencies, funeral parlors and other service providers to ensure that referred clients are able to receive the needed services immediately. Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) may be entered into by the LGU with qualified service providers in accordance with pertinent regulations.

We recommended the following:

Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with at least one member each from the Accounting Unit and GSO and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;

After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:

Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);

Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;

Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any; and

Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

Enjoin the General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards and conduct physical inventory of all municipal properties and to prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;

D. Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards;

E. Provide the GSO Designate with an office and enough manpower to support his function and to lighten his load in the Treasury Office;

F. Transfer the PPE accounts booked under the Trust Fund to the General Fund and recognize the depreciation in the General Fund books;

G. Direct the GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to prepare the road map of the municipality to facilitate the preparation of a proper inventory and reporting of the municipality’s road network system; and

H. Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended that the management:

Require the Municipal GSO and/ or other responsible officials to obtain from the donor/s Deed/s of Donation and require the Municipal Accountant to record the items at its fair value;

Streamline and document its donation policy and process thru the issuance of an Executive Order or a Memorandum which among others, would contain the employees authorized to receive donations and their reportorial responsibilities.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the MNAO to secure the Acknowledgement Receipt of In-Kind Donations and submit it to management for its inclusion in the related quarterly report;
Require the MNAO to conduct inventory taking and assessment of the donated items to ascertain completeness and conformance to quality;
Direct the MNAO to transfer the donated goods to a secure and suitable location limiting access to those with direct accountability over the items.

We recommended that management:
Require the MAO, MNAO and the LDRRMO to submit to the GSO and the Municipal Accountant the Acknowledgement Receipts of the donations they have received and the list of beneficiaries with whom the donations were distributed, copy furnished the Office of the Auditor;
Streamline and document its donation policy and process thru the issuance of an Executive Order or a Memorandum, which among others, would contain the employees authorized to receive donations and their reportorial responsibilities.

We recommended that management:
Direct the MHO and the MENRO to coordinate with the DOH on the best course of action for the transport and disposal of COVID-19 wastes;
Instruct the MENRO to integrate COVID-19 Waste Management Plan in the LGU’s Solid Waste Management Plan;
Advice the Local Development Council to review the programs under the Annual Investment Plan for the possible inclusion of program related to COVID-19 Waste Management;

We recommended that management:
Direct the PHWs to file for claim on hazard pay differential but should the benefit be not granted, may we alternatively require the concerned office of the LGU to submit to the Office of the Auditor a written explanation on its reasons supported with the SCBAA and the SAAOB;
Enjoin the MHO, the MBO, and the members of the Sangguniang Bayan to review the adequacy and reasonableness of Hazard Pay appropriation in the C.Y. 2022 Annual Budget.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the HRMO to prepare an organizational chart governing the market operation, in consultation with the MEEDO Head, Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer;
Direct the HRMO to review the personnel schedule, and include in the job descriptions, the authority, responsibilities, and reporting lines for the related positions;
Call on the Municipal Treasurer and the MEEDO Head to strictly enforce segregation of duties in the collection and recording function of rental fees from market stalls;
Order the MEEDO Head and the Market Supervisor to submit to the Office of the Auditor a copy of the updated ledger as of December 31, 2021, showing the payments posted for each stallholders, and their unpaid balance, if any.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record and adjust the balances of subject inventories;
Call-on the GSO to submit to the Municipal Accountant the Distribution List covering the difference on the welfare goods accounted by the audit team;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly follow the accounting standard and accounting policies on inventories amidst continued purchase and consumption;
Enjoin the Municipal Health Officer, the GSO, and the HRMO to conduct coordination meetings on improving the existing set-up of medicine dispensation and accounting through review of personnel functions, manpower complement and assignment of tasks.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the iTax service-provider for a systems upgrade with the two-fold goal to hasten data processing and provide additional program functions; otherwise, consider sourcing another service provider to deliver the needed service;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accountant the List of Basic RPT Delinquencies since C.Y. 2002, as reference of the accountant’s adjustment in the RPT and SET receivables.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the Market Supervisor to secure copies of lease contract for all stallholders as baseline document of future verification and monitoring;
Urge the members Sangguniang Bayan and the MEEDO to revisit                           M.O. No. 20-17 for possible amendments thereon, including the determination of actual number of stalls available for rent;
Direct the collecting officers to enforce and collect the rates prescribed by the ordinance, otherwise a Notice of Charge will be issued for the amount of deficiency due the government, chargeable against the persons liable.

observations.managementAction:
Various programs were implemented such as: 

Capacitation of SWM LGU Enforcers; 

Conduct revisit, re-orientation of proper segregation at source; 

Garbage Collectors must collect segregated solid waste only; 

No Garbage fee No Segregation No Collection; 

Enforcement of Fines and Penalties

Direct the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board to make effective plan to address the problem on garbage collection to cover at least the majority of its Barangays; 

Residual Containment Area was built at Sebac, 

Only metro Barangays/Schools solid wastes were collected;

 33 Barangays have their own MRF; 

Direct the MENRO – designate to closely monitor and ensure that projects relative to solid waste management are implemented as scheduled; and 

Early monitoring and coordination being done every now and then at the market place, municipal premises and metro barangays and schools; attended ABC Meeting; 

Coordinated/Facilitated clean-up drive at the Estero Canal and Coastal Areas; Conducted inspection at possible dump garbage along the shore at Cabol-anonan and Barra; Bag-making Project. 

Assisted MGB area validation at Yahong; Facilitated area inspection at Colambutan Settlement Farm School; 

Conducted dialogue with occupants to present the area for establishment of SLF; 

Prepared necessary documents and finally the propose area will be surveyed as soon as possible to compe up with the Technical Description and to request with the MGB an ocular inspection and validation for appropriate area of sanitary landfill.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the management the following:

Require the LDRRMO and Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the proper National Government Agency for the infrastructure audit of the evacuation centers or selection of the suitable sites and proper design in case of building permanent evacuation centers, as the case may be; and

Require the LDRRMO to address the herein noted lacking facilities and the deficiencies that may be noted in infrastructure audit;

In light of the foregoing circumstances, we recommended that management:
Instruct the MAO and the GSO to validate the existence and current condition of the dispersed livestock based on available list of beneficiaries;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit to COA a request for relief of accountability by supporting available documents in accordance with existing rules and requirements for the relief;
Otherwise we recommended that management:
Consider the practicality of treating the dispersal as a grant whereby ownership was deemed transferred from the local government to the listed beneficiaries, to be formalized by enjoining the Sangguniang Bayan to pass a resolution on that regard;
Direct the MAO to obtain a Sworn Statement of receipt of biological assetsissued by the beneficiaries as supporting document for the grant;
Instruct the MAO to conduct an intensive monitoring and evaluation if similar programs will be carried out in the future.

We recommended that management:
Direct the Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the DPWH in the identification of streetlights that will be reconstructed and endorse to the Municipal Development Council to realign the budgetary provision of streetlights reconstruction should overlapping of works be verified;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to closely coordinate the completion of streetlights reconstruction by the DPWH;
Instruct the MPDC to request from the concerned DPWH officials the list of projects that will be undertaken in the municipality to complement the planning and funding of development programs;
Enter into an ADRRI with the IO on upcoming projects and demand compliance from the IO should the local government be confronted in like circumstances.

We have recommended that management:

Direct the Municipal Account to:

Properly prepare and maintain the required PPE Ledger Cards for each class of PPE, listing therein the data as to its acquisition, description, custody, useful life and other necessary information;
Coordinate with GSO in the reconciliation of accounting records and physical inventory; 
Exercise extra care in providing for depreciation to avoid errors and inconsistencies leading to misstatements of the accounts; and 
Draw Journal Entry Voucher to record the unrecognized Depreciation Expense;

Direct the General Services Officer to:

Coordinate and work closely with the Municipal Accountant in the reconciliation of property records; and
Maintain properly accomplished property cards for each category of PPE listed in the accounting records and ensure that the balances shown thereon agree with the prepared RPCPPE and the book balances.

We recommended that management:

Enforce strict implementation of the prescribed procedures and guidelines under RA 9003 on the solid waste segregation at source;

Direct the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board to make effective plan to address the problem on garbage collection to cover at least the majority of its Barangays;

Direct the MENRO – designate to closely monitor and ensure that projects relative to solid waste management are implemented as scheduled; and 

Exert earnest effort to fast-track acquisition and construction of Sanitary Landfill in compliance with Section 37 of RA 9003.

